        Auction vs Private Treaty in Brisbane: How Sellers Should Choose
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Choosing between auction and private treaty is one of the most consequential decisions you make before listing. Here is how to think through the choice clearly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most vendors have a preference before they sit down with an agent, and most agents have a preference they push. Neither approach is automatically right. The choice between auction and private treaty should come down to your property, your local market conditions, the buyer profile most likely to purchase your home, and how much certainty you need by what date. Getting this decision right before you sign the Form 6 is worth more than almost any other preparation decision you will make.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What actually separates the two methods</h2>
      <p>Auction is a public, competitive bidding process with a fixed date and no cooling-off period for registered bidders. A reserve price is set privately before the event. If bidding reaches the reserve, the property sells unconditionally on the day. If it does not reach the reserve, it passes in and negotiations continue, usually with the highest bidder first. The defining feature of auction for sellers is that it creates a deadline, which concentrates buyer activity and can eliminate conditions. The defining disadvantage is that if buyer competition is thin on the day, you can find yourself negotiating from a weaker position than you would have had with private treaty.</p>

      <p>Private treaty is a negotiated sale. You set a price guide, buyers inspect and make offers, and your agent works through those offers to achieve the best result. Buyers can include conditions, most commonly finance approval and a building and pest inspection. The campaign has no fixed end date, though most run for four to six weeks. Private treaty works best when the pool of ready unconditional buyers is smaller, when the property is harder to value through comparable sales, or when your likely buyers need time to arrange finance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When auction works best in Brisbane's inner east</h2>
      <p>Auction produces consistently strong results in Brisbane's inner east when several conditions are present at once. Strong buyer demand in the suburb, meaning multiple buyers actively competing for each listing, is the most important factor. When two or three genuine buyers want your property, auction forces them to bid against each other publicly. That competitive pressure is what generates the premium above reserve that makes auction worthwhile. In suburbs like Bulimba, Hawthorne, and Norman Park, where demand has consistently outpaced supply, auction clearance rates regularly run above 70 percent, which means most auctions produce a sale.</p>

      <p>Unique or hard-to-replicate properties also suit auction. A home with an unusual floor plan, a large block, river views, or an architect-designed renovation is difficult to value precisely from comparable sales. Private treaty requires a price guide that anchors buyer expectations. Auction removes that anchor and lets competitive bidding determine the ceiling. If your property genuinely has features that will appeal to buyers who rarely find what they are looking for, auction lets that scarcity work in your favour.</p>

      <p>Sellers with a fixed timeline also benefit from auction. If you need to transact within a specific window, an auction campaign of three to four weeks with a set date gives you a predictable endpoint. Private treaty campaigns can drift if the right buyer takes time to find, and that uncertainty can be costly if you have a purchase deadline or other time pressure on your side.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When private treaty is the stronger choice</h2>
      <p>Private treaty tends to work better when your most likely buyers need conditions. First home buyers, buyers who have not yet sold their own property, and buyers purchasing investment properties often cannot go unconditional at auction. If the buyer pool for your property includes a large proportion of these purchasers, running an auction effectively excludes your strongest bidders from the process. You may achieve a sale, but it will be with whoever happens to be in a position to bid unconditionally on the day, which is not always your best buyer.</p>

      <p>Properties that are harder to value also present challenges at auction. If there are few genuinely comparable recent sales in your street or suburb, setting a credible reserve is difficult. Agents may be tempted to set the reserve conservatively to avoid a pass-in, which can mean you sell below what private treaty negotiation might have achieved with a properly qualified buyer over three to four weeks.</p>

      <p>In softer market conditions, when buyer competition is lower and clearance rates have fallen, private treaty often outperforms auction. The artificial deadline of auction day can expose a lack of depth in the buyer pool. A well-run private treaty campaign gives your agent more time and flexibility to find the right buyer and work through their position, rather than relying on whoever shows up on one particular Saturday.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The EOI hybrid and when it makes sense</h2>
      <p>Expressions of interest (EOI) campaigns ask buyers to submit their best offer by a set date and time. The vendor then reviews all offers and selects a preferred buyer to negotiate with. EOI is sometimes positioned as a middle ground between auction and private treaty, and it does have genuine advantages for certain properties. It creates a deadline without requiring unconditional buyers, which means conditional buyers can participate. It also gives your agent leverage in negotiations because multiple offers can be compared simultaneously.</p>

      <p>The weakness of EOI is that it lacks the public competitive pressure of auction. Buyers do not know what others have offered, which means they cannot bid up in response to competition. Some buyer advisers will deliberately counsel their clients to hold back in an EOI process, submit just enough to get into the negotiation room, and then negotiate from there. Whether EOI suits your property depends on whether the primary benefit you need is buyer participation (which EOI delivers) or competitive price tension (which auction delivers better).</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the data shows about auction premiums locally</h2>
      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, well-run auctions in strong market conditions do generate a measurable premium over private treaty in comparable sales. The premium is real but not universal. It appears most consistently when more than two registered bidders are competing on the day and when the property is genuinely scarce for its type. When only one bidder is registered, the auction process tends to produce a price very close to the reserve, which is effectively the same outcome as a strong private treaty offer from that buyer anyway. The premium comes from competition, not from the auction format itself.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions to ask before you sign the Form 6</h2>
      <p>Before committing to a method, ask your agent to be specific about the buyer profile most likely to purchase your property and whether those buyers are typically in a position to bid unconditionally at auction. Ask what the current clearance rate is for comparable properties in your suburb over the past 90 days. Ask whether there are two or more genuine buyers currently in the market who are likely to compete for your property, and how your agent knows this. Ask what happens if the property passes in: how will the agent manage the negotiation, and at what point does a passed-in price become a problem.</p>

      <p>An agent who can answer these questions with specific local data is giving you useful information. An agent who defaults to recommending auction for every property because it creates urgency, or who defaults to private treaty because they find auction day stressful, is telling you about their own preferences rather than what is right for your situation.</p>

